{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"50fbd2b5-7fe0-422c-893d-b2add9107fb0","content":"There's no relevant documentation in this repository, but here's the general approach for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump without `createdump`\n\n1. **Check for macOS crash reports** — macOS automatically captures crash logs:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for files matching your process name (`.ips` or `.crash` extension).\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before the next run:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n   After the crash, the core file appears at the configured path.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Use `bt` for a backtrace, `thread list`, `frame variable`, etc.\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily adjust SIP settings or use `lldb` to attach live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb -- /path/to/your/app [args]\n   ```\n\nSince NativeAOT produces a native binary (no CoreCLR), standard macOS/LLDB debugging workflows apply directly — no managed dump tooling (`dotnet-dump`) is needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"14612852-eefa-444f-a298-1047cd7ee848","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository is empty. The user is asking a general knowledge question about recovering crash dumps on macOS for NativeAOT apps. Let me answer from my knowledge.","outputTokens":392,"requestId":"D7C1:11B452:10602E1:12B7199:69F2B59F"},"id":"9d04cee5-9dd8-431b-aae5-93e3feb12ad4","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:51:38.345Z","parentId":"cf9e598a-ad1a-4115-90fc-5bdb50135f19"}
